## 14. How Temporary UI State Is Different From Game State

This project uses an important separation:

- permanent state goes into Redux
- temporary presentation state stays local to React

Examples of temporary state:

- whether the deck viewer modal is open
- current hand visual ordering
- whether a play sequence animation is active
- which cards are visually "locked" during telegraphing

This is good because these details affect experience, not core rules.

If you stored too much of this in Redux, the store would become noisy and harder to reason about.

