## 15. Hand Sorting Architecture

The hand sorting logic is split into:

- `src/ui/screens/run-screen/handSort.ts`
- `src/ui/screens/run-screen/useHandState.ts`

### `handSort.ts`

Contains pure helpers:

- comparing by rank
- comparing by suit
- sorting hand order
- syncing old order against new cards
- rebuilding ordered hand arrays

This file has no React logic.

That is exactly how pure domain-ish helpers should look.

### `useHandState.ts`

This hook owns only hand order behavior:

- current sort mode
- current order IDs
- automatic reset to rank sort when hand contents change
- manual reorder mode when cards are dragged

This is a strong pattern:

- pure functions define the rules
- hook manages when to apply them

That is one of the best ways to build interactive React game systems.

---

## 16. Play Telegraphing Architecture

One of the most educational parts of the UI is the staged play sequence.

The actual reducer still plays instantly.

But the player should not experience it instantly.

So the project separates:

- rule commit
- presentation sequence

That logic is split into:

- `src/ui/screens/run-screen/playSequence.ts`
- `src/ui/screens/run-screen/usePlaySequence.ts`
- `src/ui/screens/run-screen/PlayField.tsx`

### `playSequence.ts`

Pure helpers:

- choose selected cards in current visual order
- create a play sequence object
- count one card into the sequence
- compute preview from current counted chips
- expose locked card IDs

### `usePlaySequence.ts`

React orchestration:

- starts the sequence
- schedules timed card counts
- calls sound functions
- resolves actual play action after the animation
- clears itself when done

This is a very useful React game pattern.

The idea is:

- keep the true rule update simple
- build the richer player experience as a temporary staged flow on top of it

### `PlayField.tsx`

Pure render component for:

- showing played cards
- showing which cards have counted
- showing live chips/mult/total during the sequence

This keeps rendering logic out of the hook and out of the screen wrapper.

